The opposite of this is even more striking. Some patient might have a chronic disease with debilitating symptoms ruining his life for many years but if he's somehow cured he will just forget about it in the matter of hours or days and go back to normal like nothing ever happened.

I think someone can have an absolutely miserable life but if he somehow gets his happy ending he will look back at it and see only the good parts. All's Well That Ends Well. Also why you should still try to "live life" if you're depressed/unwell. You will remember it differently.

Similarly if you go on a vacation/trip and get sick but force yourself to still go sightseeing, visit art galleries, etc. you will filter the sickness out and just remember the fun parts on their own. Your past is in some ways just a projection of your current state back in time.

This guy flew commercial passenger airplanes and even worked as a flying instructor for decades with a revoked pilot's license that he had half a photocopy of because in pilot culture it was considered rude to ask to see someone's license, a leftover tradition from the Old West.

Had multiple airplane crashes and survived them all. "That guy had the damnedest license I ever saw: all he had was about half of a photostatic copy of a private license that had been revoked eleven years previously. And he had been flying commercially with it for all that time."
